\par
Alright \f4\u-10179?\u-9139?\f0  since you chose 4, let\rquote s explain how hackers attack each layer of the OSI Model in real life, one step at a time and in very simple language.\par
\par
Remember: the OSI model has 7 layers, and attackers can target each layer differently.\par
\par
1. Layer 1 \f2\emdash  Physical Layer Attack\par
\par
This layer deals with hardware and cables.\par
\par
Examples:\par
\par
Ethernet cables\par
\par
Network cards\par
\par
Switch ports\par
\par
Wi-Fi signals\par
\par
How attackers exploit it\par
\par
An attacker may:\par
\par
\bullet  plug a rogue device into a company network\par
\bullet  physically tap a cable to capture traffic\par
\bullet  steal hardware\par
\bullet  install malicious USB devices\par
\par
Example attack:\par
Someone secretly connects a small hacking device to a network port inside an office.\par
\par
Cybersecurity prevention:\par
\par
physical security\par
\par
locked server rooms\par
\par
CCTV cameras\par
\par
port security\par
\par
2. Layer 2 \emdash  Data Link Layer Attack\par
\par
This layer uses MAC addresses to identify devices in a local network.\par
\par
Protocols here include:\par
\par
Ethernet\par
\par
Address Resolution Protocol\par
\par
Common attack\par
\par
ARP Spoofing\par
\par
How it works (simple):\par
\par
A hacker joins the same network.\par
\par
The hacker pretends to be the router.\par
\par
Devices send their traffic to the hacker instead.\par
\par
This allows the hacker to:\par
\par
intercept passwords\par
\par
monitor data\par
\par
manipulate traffic\par
\par
Protection:\par
\par
ARP inspection\par
\par
network segmentation\par
\par
secure switches\par
\par
3. Layer 3 \emdash  Network Layer Attack\par
\par
This layer uses IP addresses to route data across networks.\par
\par
Main protocol:\par
\par
Internet Protocol\par
\par
Common attacks\par
\par
IP Spoofing\par
\par
What happens:\par
\par
The attacker changes their IP address to appear like another device.\par
\par
Why hackers do this:\par
\par
hide identity\par
\par
bypass security\par
\par
launch bigger attacks\par
\par
Another attack:\par
\par
Packet Sniffing\par
\par
This allows attackers to capture network packets and analyze them.\par
\par
Protection:\par
\par
packet filtering\par
\par
intrusion detection systems\par
\par
network monitoring\par
\par
4. Layer 4 \emdash  Transport Layer Attack\par
\par
This layer manages data delivery and reliability.\par
\par
Protocols used here:\par
\par
Transmission Control Protocol\par
\par
User Datagram Protocol\par
\par
Common attack\par
\par
SYN Flood Attack\par
\par
Simple explanation:\par
\par
A server receives a request to start a connection.\par
\par
The attacker sends thousands of fake requests.\par
\par
The server becomes overloaded.\par
\par
Real users cannot connect.\par
\par
This is a type of Distributed Denial-of-Service Attack.\par
\par
Protection:\par
\par
rate limiting\par
\par
firewalls\par
\par
load balancing\par
\par
5. Layer 5 \emdash  Session Layer Attack\par
\par
This layer manages sessions between two devices.\par
\par
Example:\par
When you log into a website.\par
\par
Attack example\par
\par
Session Hijacking\par
\par
How it works:\par
\par
A user logs into a website.\par
\par
The hacker steals the session ID.\par
\par
The hacker uses it to access the account.\par
\par
The system thinks the hacker is the real user.\par
\par
Protection:\par
\par
session encryption\par
\par
secure cookies\par
\par
short session timeouts\par
\par
6. Layer 6 \emdash  Presentation Layer Attack\par
\par
This layer manages:\par
\par
encryption\par
\par
compression\par
\par
data formatting\par
\par
Common technologies:\par
\par
Secure Sockets Layer\par
\par
Transport Layer Security\par
\par
Attack example\par
\par
SSL Stripping\par
\par
What happens:\par
\par
A website normally uses HTTPS.\par
\par
The attacker forces the connection to HTTP.\par
\par
Data becomes unencrypted.\par
\par
Now the attacker can see:\par
\par
passwords\par
\par
messages\par
\par
sensitive data\par
\par
Protection:\par
\par
HTTPS\par
\par
TLS encryption\par
\par
HSTS security policies\par
\par
7. Layer 7 \emdash  Application Layer Attack\par
\par
This is the most targeted layer by hackers.\par
\par
Why?\par
\par
Because it interacts directly with users and applications.\par
\par
Protocols here include:\par
\par
Hypertext Transfer Protocol\par
\par
File Transfer Protocol\par
\par
Simple Mail Transfer Protocol\par
\par
Common attacks\par
\par
SQL Injection\par
\par
Example:\par
\par
A hacker enters malicious code into a website login form.\par
\par
This can allow the attacker to:\par
\par
access databases\par
\par
steal user information\par
\par
bypass login systems\par
\par
Another attack:\par
\par
Cross-Site Scripting\par
\par
This injects malicious scripts into websites.\par
\par
Protection:\par
\par
input validation\par
\par
secure coding\par
\par
web application firewalls\par
\par
Simple Way to Understand Everything\par
\par
Think of the OSI model like a building with 7 floors.\par
\par
Each floor has different security risks.\par
\par
Floor\tab What Happens\tab Attack Example\par
